    <section class="INTRODUCTION">
        <h1>INTRODUCTION</h1>
        <p>Socotra is a botanical treasure chest unlike anywhere else on Earth. <br>
        Its long isolation has led to the evolution of a stunning array of <br>
        endemic plants—species found nowhere else.
</p>
    </section>
    
    <section class="plant_welth">
        <p>here is a group of the most common endemic plants in <strong>Socotra</strong> :</p>
        <ol>
            <li><h2>Dragon's Blood Tree:</h2>

            <h3>OVERVIEW</h3>
            <dl>
                <dt>Appearance:</dt>
                <dd>Umbrella-shaped crown with dense foliage; looks like a giant mushroom from afar.</dd>
            </dl>
            <dt>Unique Trait:</dt>
            <DD> Produces a crimson resin known as “dragon's blood”,
                <br> used historically as medicine, dye, and incense.
            </DD>
            <dd>Ecological Role:</dd>
            <dt>Its shape helps shade the roots and reduce evaporation 
                <br>an adaptation to Socotra's arid climate.
            </dt>
            <li><h2>Bottle Tree <em>Adenium obesum socotranum</em> :</h2></li>


            <h3>OVERVIEW</h3>
            <dl>
                <dt>Appearance:</dt>
                <dd>Swollen, bottle-like trunk with vibrant red-and-white flowers;
                    <br>grows up to 3 meters tall.
                </dd>
                <dt>Adaptation:</dt>
                <dd> Stores water in its thick trunk to survive long dry seasons.
                </dd>
            </dl>
            <li><h2>Frankincense Tree <em>Boswellia sacra </em></h2> :</li>


            <h3>OVERVIEW</h3>
            <dl>
                <dt>Appearance:</dt>
                <dd>Gnarled trunk with papery bark; grows 2-8 meters tall.
                </dd>
                <dt>Product:</dt>
                <dd>Yields aromatic resin (frankincense) 
                    <br>used in perfumes, incense, and traditional medicine.</dd>
                <dt>Harvesting:</dt>
                <dd>Resin is collected by making small cuts in the bark;
                    <br>it hardens into fragrant granules</dd>
            </dl>
        </ol>

    </section>


